In a similar fashion as Airbnb, it would be efficient to help handling this issue with a declarative approach. As such, part of the solution would be to use something close to the example below. We would have to first declare the layout breakpoints of the application on top of the component tree.

```javascript
import { BreakpointProvider } from '../breakpoints/Breakpoints';
import { DESKTOP, MOBILE, TABLET } from '../breakpoints/BreakpointConstants';

ReactDOM.render(
  <BrowserRouter>
    <BreakpointProvider mobile={MOBILE} tablet={TABLET} desktop={DESKTOP}>
      <App />
    </BreakpointProvider>
  </BrowserRouter>,
  document.getElementById('root')
);
```

And later in the component tree, we would be able to use those breakpoints to define whether or not some components should be rendered:

```javascript
import { TABLET } from '../breakpoints/BreakpointConstants';
import { Hide } from '../breakpoints/Hide';
import { Show } from '../breakpoints/Show';

const Dashboard = () => {
  return (
    <div>
      <Show aboveOrEqual={TABLET}>
        <LargeCard />
      </Show>
      <Hide above={TABLET}>
        <SmallCard />
      </Hide>
    </div>
  );
};
```

In this example, the dashboard would display large cards for a tablet or a desktop and small cards on a mobile. The application would come with a set of predefined breakpoints with at least (mobile, tablet and desktop).

After a review of the way loading is handled by major users of React, the Loading component should probably be removed altogether. Instead, the loading state should become a concern handled by each component. This concern may not be relevant for every component by the way.

As such once a state container is in a loading state, it should indicate to the appropriate components to switch to a loading state. For that a better solution would to use the following pseudo code:

```javascript
import { LoadingConsumer } from '../loading/Loading';

const TestCard = () => {
  return (
    <LoadingConsumer>
      { isLoading => 
        <Card>
          <Image isLoading={isLoading} />
          <Text isLoading={isLoading} />
        </Card>
      }
    </LoadingConsumer>
  );
};
```

In this example, while the page is loading, both the image and the title of the card will display a placeholder. In such situation, the elements of the user interface will not jump all over the place once the loading is completed. The loading policy of this component will work regardless of where this component is used.

We won't be able to efficiently handle this issue globally, it needs to be become a component specific issue.

## Steps to reproduce

1. Open a project and select a semantic element with several properties in the explorer.
2. Open the browser's dev tools on the _Network_ tab.
3. Click on one of the widgets in the properties view.
4. In the _Network_ tab find the `graphql` request which sent the `operationName: "updateWidgetFocus"`
5. The _Response_ for this request is always:

```json
{
  "data": {
    "updateWidgetFocus": {
      "__typename": "ErrorPayload",
      "message": "An unexpected error has occurred, please contact the server administrator"
    }
  }
}
```

## Analysis

When receiving a `UpdateWidgetFocusInput`, `MutationUpdateWidgetFocusDataFetcher` dispatches the event to `IProjectEventProcessorRegistry`. It ends up being treated by `FormEventProcessor.handle(IRepresentationInput, Context)`, which delegates to the supplied `IWidgetSubscriptionManager`, but the subscription updates are sent asynchrnously, and `FormEventProcessor.handle` does not return any value in this case. The default `Optional.empty()` is interpreted by `MutationUpdateWidgetFocusDataFetcher` as an error, so it returns an unexpected error payload.

