If the solution we take is to keep the event processor alive a little longer, this can be done (for the case of _Forms_) by adding a delay in `org.eclipse.sirius.web.spring.collaborative.forms.FormEventProcessor.canBeDisposed()`:

```java
    @Override
    public Flux<Boolean> canBeDisposed() {
        return this.canBeDisposedSink.asFlux().delayElements(Duration.ofSeconds(5));
    }
```

It seems to work in practice, but feels quite _ad hoc_ and "smelly":
- which delay to use, and why?
- should the apply to all dialects?

It feels like there should be a more reliable way to detect that the event processor is *really* no longer needed, but I'm not sure as the front (and the network) can have an arbitrary lag and in theory we could receive events targetting an "inactive" event processor at any point in the future.

If we can not to better than adding a delay, we should also send some feedback to the client telling it the the request was dropped (and let it surface the info the end-user if relevant). AFAICT currently we simply log a message on the backend ("No representation event processor found for event") and send a generic "unexpected error" to the client (maybe).

