Currently when creating a new top-level element inside a model, the dialog that opens provides a select box which presents all the available domains:

![Capture d’écran de 2021-12-15 09-55-07](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10608/146155322-c4161b66-a446-4162-8b37-b502eee5970f.png)

The domains are presented using their technical ids (nsURI), which is not very user-friendly (to say the least).
This is made worse by the pseudo-random names used currently for dynamic domains, which are completely unrelated to what is actually inside the domain.

The primary name exposed to end-users for domains should be a human-readable one.
For statically registered EMF domains, we could improve the way we register them.

Instead of:
```java
@Configuration
public class SampleEMFConfiguration {

    @Bean
    public EPackage flowEPackage() {
        return FlowPackage.eINSTANCE;
    }

    @Bean
    public AdapterFactory flowAdapterFactory() {
        return new FlowItemProviderAdapterFactory();
    }

    @Bean
    public ILabelFeatureProvider flowLabelFeatureProvider() {
        return new LabelFeatureProvider(FlowPackage.eINSTANCE.getNsURI(), new FlowLabelFeatureSwitch(), new FlowEditableSwitch());
    }
}
```

we could allow for registering richer domain definitions as consitent whole (instead of separate pacakge/adapter-factory/etc.

Something like:

```java
@Configuration
public class SampleConfiguration {

    @Bean
    public DomainDefinition flowDomain() {
        return DomainDefinition.newEMFBasedDomain("Flow") // a user-friendly name
                               .description("Define hardware systems with data flows between components")
                               .icon("icons/FlowDomain.svg")
                               .ePackage(FlowPackage.eINSTANCE)
                               .adapterFactory(new FlowItemProviderAdapterFactory())
                               .labelFeatureProvider(FlowPackage.eINSTANCE.getNsURI(), new FlowLabelFeatureSwitch(), new FlowEditableSwitch())
                               .build();
    }

    @Bean
    public DomainDefinition componentsDomain() {
        return DomainDefinition.newDomain("System Components")
                               .definition("domains/components.domain") // a static "Domain" instance
                               .build();
    }
}
```

