In the API of the form property section, some parts of the API are relying on generics but they cannot possibly work. They appear to work because they have not been applied to existing property sections and the only place where they have been applied have very lax typeScript settings and thus pretty much anything would appear to "work". The issue comes from interfaces introduced for the support of custom widgets like `PropertySectionComponent` and `PropertySectionComponentProps`. They look nice with their generic signature but they do not really work. Here are the interfaces in question:

```
export type PropertySectionComponentProps<W extends GQLWidget> = {
  editingContextId: string;
  formId: string;
  widget: W;
  subscribers: GQLSubscriber[];
  readOnly: boolean;
  setSelection: (selection: Selection) => void;
};

export type PropertySectionComponent<W extends GQLWidget> = (
  props: PropertySectionComponentProps<W>
) => JSX.Element | null;
```

In `PropertySection.tsx`, we are not using generics at all because nothing in the existing API is based on generics so the type of `widget` is `GQLWidget`:

```
const CustomWidgetComponent = propertySectionsRegistry.getComponent(widget);
```

The property section registry is not leveraging generics in its function `getComponent` at all, which is the start of our problems:

```
export type PropertySectionComponentRegistry = {
  getComponent: (widget: GQLWidget) => PropertySectionComponent<GQLWidget> | null;
};
```

Which brings us to the code which reveals the issue:

```
const propertySectionsRegistry: PropertySectionComponentRegistry = {
  getComponent: (widget: GQLWidget) => {
    if (widget.__typename === 'Slider') {
      return SliderPropertySection;
    } else if (widget.__typename === 'ReferenceWidget') {
      return ReferencePropertySection;
    }
  }
}
```

Here, we can return a `SliderPropertySection` in case of a `SQLSlider` but the `SliderPropertySection` has to follow the signature of `PropertySectionComponent<W extends GQLWidget>`. As a result, its props have the type `PropertySectionComponentProps<GQLSlider>` which indicates that it can only work if it receives a `GQLSlider` but the signature of `PropertySectionComponentRegistry#getComponent` requires a `PropertySectionComponent<GQLWidget>` which would indicate that every single widget contributed using this API should have a props typed with `PropertySectionComponent<GQLWidget>` and not `PropertySectionComponent<W extends GQLWidget>`.

One could say that the fix is quite easy, the registry should be updated to have the following signature:

```
export type PropertySectionComponentRegistry = {
  getComponent: <Widget extends GQLWidget>(widget: Widget) => PropertySectionComponent<Widget> | null;
}
```

Unfortunately this does not work since we stumble on this error:

```
Type 'PropertySectionComponentProps<Widget>' is not assignable to type 'PropertySectionComponentProps<GQLSlider>'.
      Type 'Widget' is not assignable to type 'GQLSlider'.
        Type 'GQLWidget' is missing the following properties from type 'GQLSlider': minValue, maxValue, currentValue
```

And there starts a great adventure fighting TypeScript typing system with generics...

I'm really not sure that this can really be done in TypeScript because even with conditional types, we (Sirius Components) would have to known the type of the custom widget (i.e. Slider) to create the proper signature. TypeScript cannot possibly work like Java. Unless proven otherwise, I think the API should change and remove generics because it is invalid.

If we were to move in this direction:

- The interface `PropertySectionComponent` should not use generics
- The interface `PropertySectionComponentProps` should not use generics either
- The code of our custom widgets should change to stop considering that `widget` can be a `GQLSlider` or a `GQLReferenceWidget` but instead a `GQLWidget`. This can be done with minimal impact on the existing code base with some sort of wrapper like this:

```
export const SliderWrapper = ({ widget, ...props }) => {
  if (isSlider(widget)) {
      return <Slider widget={widget} {...props} />;
  }
  return null;
}
```


TypeScript conditional types: https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/2/conditional-types.html

