If two different extensions (E1 and E2) define their own custom `IObjectServiceDelegate`, they can not both work completely at the same time.

In `ComposedObjectService.getObject(IEditingContext, String)` we do:

```java
    @Override
    public Optional<Object> getObject(IEditingContext editingContext, String objectId) {
        var optionalDelegate = this.objectServiceDelegates.stream()
                .filter(delegate -> delegate.canHandle(editingContext))
                .findFirst();
        if (optionalDelegate.isPresent()) {
            return optionalDelegate.get().getObject(editingContext, objectId);
        }
        return this.defaultObjectService.getObject(editingContext, objectId);
    }
```

If E1 and E2 want to have any chance to get their `getObject(editingContext, objectId)` method called, they currently *must* return `true` to `canHandle(editingContext)`. However, when this is the case the "first" (on the order Spring will decide to inject them) which is found by `ComposedObjectService` will be the only one invoked. If it's E1, it can resolve its own objects and the defaults (by extending `DefaultObjectService`) but  will not know about potential other objects that E2 would be able to resolve, and E2 will never be called (until maybe the next reboot if it is injected before E1 this time).

One option would be for `IObjectServiceDelegate.canHandle(IEditingContext)` to also take the `String objectId` as it is the "guard method" for `getObject(IEditingContext editingContext, String objectId)` and `getContents(IEditingContext editingContext, String objectId)`. However this means that to answer this more precise question, `canHandle(IEditingContext, String)` some (most? all?) implementations will need to actully try to resolve the designated object just to return `true` and then be called again via `getObject(IEditingContext, String)` and re-do the same work. And a third and fourth time in the (relatively common) case where the next step will be to invoke `getContents()`:

1. canHandle(editinContext, objectId) => resolve the objectId, return true if found
2. getObject(editinContext, objectId) => resolve the objectId, this time to return it
3. canHandle(editinContext, objectId) => resolve the objectId, return true if found
4. getContents(editinContext, objectId) => resolve the objectId, this time to return its children

Another option would be to remove `IObjectServiceDelegate.canHandle(IEditingContext)`, leverage the fact that `IObjectServiceDelegate.getObject()` returns an optional and change `IObjectServiceDelegate.getContents()` to return an `Optional<List<Object>>` and return the first non-empty result from all the known delegates.

Another possible change (somewhat orthogonal to the above) would be to change `getContents(IEditingContext editinContext, String objectId)` into `getContents(IEditingContext editinContext, Object object)`. In the common case where we invoke `getContents` in a context where we have already resolved the objectId this would avoid some duplicate work. A default implementation could be added to `IObjectService[Delegate]` for compatibility:

```java
  // New method, takes an already resolved object
  List<Object> getContents(IEditingContext editingContext, Object object);

  // Old method, takes the id if that's all we have and resolve it first
  default List<Object> getContents(IEditingContext editingContext, String objectId) {
    return this.getObject(editingContext, String objectId).map(this::getContents).orElse(List.of());
  }
```

= ADR-XXX - Make support for transient representations more explicit

== Context

Sirius Web contains a set of transient representations which are not as connected to the Sirius Components architecture as persistent representations.
As a result, it is difficult to obtain both the metadata and the description of a transient representation.

== Decision

We should be able to find the description of any transient representation.
For that, we will introduce a dedicated service to find them.

```
package org.eclipse.sirius.web.services.api.representations;

public interface ITransientRepresentationMetadataSearchService {
    Optional<RepresentationMetadata> findById(String editingContextId, String representationId);
}
```

```
package org.eclipse.sirius.web.services.representations;

@Service
public class TransientRepresentationMetadataSearchService implements ITransientRepresentationMetadataSearchService {
    public Optional<RepresentationMetadata> findById(String editingContextId, String representationId) {
        // hardcoded metadata for explorer, validation, details, representations, related elements
    }
}
```

We could then use this service in the `EditingContextRepresentationDataFetcher` in order to retrieve the metadata of the transient representations.

After that, we should be able to find the description of said transient representations in `EditingContext#getRepresentationDescriptions` as for any representation descriptions. For that, the editing context should be populated with the various representation descriptions when it is loaded.

== Status

Work in progress

== Consequences

We should update the behavior of `EditingContextRepresentationDataFetcher` in the future to extract it in a dedicated service `IRepresentationMetadataSearchService` which should look in either the `ITransientRepresentationMetadataSearchService` or in the database to find the metadata. I don't see why we should look in the editing context event processor with both solutions, as it is inefficient performance wise and can provide unsynchronized information.

