The "Synchronize with representation" behavior:

* has non-obvious semantics which make it confusing to end-users (even when disabled, _some kind_ of selection synchronization still happens, just only on the currently visible items);
* has historically been the cause of several (sometimes subtle) bugs and regressions;
* has a non-obvious UI (to me at least), with a plain (non-toggle) button being "normal" when the mode is active, but appearing as _disabled_ when inactive, which looks like an action that can not be performed;
* has performance impacts when enabled: for (almost?) all selection changes, at least one query to the backend to know the path of all the selected elements, and possibly one computation of a new tree subscription with a configuration set to expand all the required nodes.

Proposal:
* keep the "if an element selected e.g. in a diagram is currently visible in the explorer, mark the corresponding item as selected" behavior (what we have when the "Synchronize" mode is disabled);
* replace the "mode" with a single-shot action button modeled after the "Select opened file" action in IntelliJ: when the action is invoked, ensure all the selected elements are _visible_ in the Explorer (this may require expanding sub-trees) and then mark them selected as above.

